 Tales</i>, Chaucer's cook, ‘highte <i>Hogge</i> of Ware’, is invoked ‘Now tell on, <i>Roger</i> …’. Since Middle English spellings of the personal name are often impossible to distinguish from the nickname <i>Hog(ge)</i> ‘hog’, some early examples may be variants of   Hogg  ."]},{"name":"Hodgin","meanings":["English:","shortened form of   Hodgson   with assimilation of /s/ to the preceding consonant.","perhaps from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Hogin</i>, a diminutive of   Hodge  , though this has not yet been found in northern England."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":44,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":53,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Hodgson was born in 1505, in Hawkshead, Lancashire, England as the son of Richard Hodgson. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Fortescue. He died in 1564, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1502–Female":"1502–Surnud","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1485–1540":"1485–1540","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1575":"1575","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1502–Female":"1502–Kuollut","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1485–1540":"1485–1540","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1575":"1575","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1502–Female":"1502–Décédée","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1485–1540":"1485–1540","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1575":"1575","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre","Hawkshead, Lancashire, England":"Hawkshead, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Thomas Hodgson est né en 1505, à Hawkshead, Lancashire, Angleterre, fils de Richard Hodgson. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Margaret Fortescue. Il est décédé en 1564, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 59 ans."},"de":{"1505–1564":"1505–1564","1502–Female":"1502–Verstorben","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1485–1540":"1485–1540","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1520":"1520","1564":"1564","1575":"1575","1540":"1540","1485":"1485","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Hawkshead, L